              <tr> 
                <td height="622" valign="top" colspan="2" bgcolor="#004142">&nbsp;<table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4"><tr bgcolor="#000000"><td><font color="#FFFFFF"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial" size="6">It is your destiny</font></td></tr></table><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Rating</Font></TD><TD><IMG SRC="images/a4.gif" BORDER=0><A HREF="articleread.php3?article=30"><IMG SRC="images/aread.GIF" BORDER=0></A><A HREF="articlereview.php3?article=30"><IMG SRC="images/areview.GIF" BORDER=0></A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Author</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2"><A HREF="../membercenter/directory/memberpage.php3?member=29">Michael "rayc" Hawley</A></FONT></TD></TR><!-- 29 --><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Description</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">This article looks at some methods of controling your(and your opponents') destiny draws.</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font face="Haettenschweiler, Tahoma, Arial, sans-serif" size="5" COLOR="#FFFFFF">Article</Font></TD><TD><font face="Arial, sans-serif" size="2">The destiny draw is intended to represent the element of chance in SWCCG.  Chance? Hah! The extent to which a player can nullify this element of chance is an indicator of how successful s/he will be. There are two main elements to destiny manipulation.<br>
<br>
Self control<br>
The first and more obvious element is taking control of your own destiny.  In the very early game this is done by having a good awareness of your chances of drawing destiny within a particular range.  Later it is done by tracking specific cards so that you draw them at the desired time.<br>
<br>
These are some key methods of controlling your own destiny:<br>
<br>
Know your deck! I mean know every card, what it does and what its destiny number is.  This is key, especially in the early game when it is harder to track specific cards. If you know the odds of drawing a particular destiny, you can make intelligent decisions about which cards to play.<br>
<br>
For instance, if you have 30 cards in your reserve deck and you know that<br>
&amp;#61623; 6 of them must be locations,<br>
&amp;#61623; 10 of them destiny 1 and 2 characters and interrupts,<br>
&amp;#61623; 8 of them destiny 3 characters and interrupts,<br>
&amp;#61623; 4 of them destiny 4 interrupts and effects, and<br>
&amp;#61623; 2 of them destiny 5 interrupts,<br>
then you might not want to initiate an Epic Duel this turn. Sure, you might draw a 5 and a 4; but you are much more likely to draw a 1 and a 0. This kind of knowledge can determine the course of a game.  The case above is pretty obvious  if Vader loses the duel and gets placed out of play, the Dark side is probably toast. But there are other cases that can be damaging as well, for instance,  you could waste a Sniper or destiny adding lost interrupt and not have them later when your destinies are stacked better (see below).<br>
<br>
Do the math! When you see a desirable destiny card go into your used pile, remember what position it holds in the used pile and count your reserve deck.  Then recycle. After you have activated (or drawn for destiny) all the cards in your reserve deck plus the number of cards that were above the desired card in your used pile, the next card will be the desired destiny.  This is destiny tracking. There are many cards that can help with destiny tracking. Here are a few:<br>
<br>
&amp;#61623; Traffic Control/Reactor Terminal  -- Put your High destiny cards into your used pile during your control phase. Then draw them for destiny on your next turn.<br>
&amp;#61623; High destiny used interrupts like Dark Manuvers, A Few Manuvers, Shocking Information/Revelation, Keep Your Eyes Open, Omni Box/Bith Shuffle, etc. Play them whenever you want and remember where they are in you used pile.<br>
&amp;#61623; Force retrieval cards --  Baraguins, for instance, lose a Bionic Hand to a force drain. Then use a Baraguins game text to retrieve the destiny 7 card into your used pile. You can use any card that lets you retrieve the top card in your lost pile, just make sure that that card is a desirable destiny.<br>
&amp;#61623; Yoda Stew same as the Traffic Control/Reactor Terminal really except that you put the cards into your force pile during your opponents turn. So you have to use the force in order to get it back into your reserve deck.<br>
&amp;#61623; Electrobinoculars	Theres nothing like a sure thing (almost). Pay the force until you see the card you want.<br>
&amp;#61623; The Dark Path  Painful, you lose 2 cards and I generally wouldnt recommend it; but one of the most beautiful SWCCG moments I ever saw involved this card.	A young friend of mine was playing against a more experienced opponent in a tournament. When my friend deployed the card the opponent remarked that it was one of the stupidest cards in the game. A turn later, my friend used it to rig a destiny draw for his Thermal Detonator. It won him the game!<br>
&amp;#61623; R2-Q2  Can be useful. A lot of players forget its peeking ability.<br>
&amp;#61623; Lift Tube Escape  Put those destiny 6 Lift Tubes back in your deck along with the high destiny used interrupt that lets you do it<br>
.<br>
<br>
<br>
Control your opponents destiny:<br>
This is a little harder and less exact but it can be very effective  especially against an opponent who is carefully tracking a few high destinies in a generally low destiny deck.  In this case you are usually not trying to make your opponent draw a specific card. Instead you are trying to either disrupt his/her card tracking or learn what destinies s/he is going to draw.	Manipulator decks can also seek to put opponents low destiny characters into his/her used pile or rearrange the force pile so that lower destiny characters are likely to go to the used pile.<br>
<br>
&amp;#61623; Force pile manipulation. -- A Dangerous Time and Shasa Tiel can be used to rearrange the opponents force pile. You can place the lower destiny cards in the part of the force pile that you think the opponent is more likely to spend.  Broken Concentration can also be used to place one of the cards you just reordered on top of the reserve deck.<br>
&amp;#61623; Reserve Deck Shuffling  If you think that your opponent has set up a destiny draw, play Bith Shuffle or Omni Box to break up his/her plans. This especially fun to do against the Light side after they just spent eleventy million force via the electrobinoculars to rig just the right destiny.<br>
&amp;#61623; Forced Activation	Cards like Beru Stew that force your opponent to activate force can get those rigged destinies of the top of the reserve deck as well.<br>
<br>
<br>
Of course there are many other tricks like those mentioned above.  I hope some of you find this useful.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
